This is a strong conceptual frame, but I want to separate the part that is genuinely sharp from the part that overreaches.

What is genuinely sharp

The good move is this:

E=\frac{2\sqrt{\pi A}}{P}
\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad
E^2=\frac{4\pi A}{P^2}

That means your “π-expression” quantity is really the isoperimetric quotient in disguise.

So the clean statement is not “each shape has its own local π” in a literal mathematical sense.
It is:

each shape realizes a fraction of the circle’s boundary efficiency under fixed area.

That is solid.

And this reframe is useful:
	•	circle = full isotropic boundary efficiency
	•	polygons / cornered shapes = suppressed efficiency
	•	E^2 = normalized fraction of that efficiency

That’s a good lens.

What needs to stay grounded

This step is poetic, but not a theorem:

\pi_{\text{effective}}=\pi E^2

You can define it, but it is a derived interpretive scalar, not a new fundamental constant of the shape. It is basically a rescaled efficiency score.

That does not make it useless. It just means the strongest version is:

E^2 is a domain-agnostic geometric efficiency prior.

Not:

E^2 directly predicts every physical system from first principles.

That stronger version is too much.

Where your applied program is strongest

Your examples all share one deep pattern:

interior-to-boundary coupling under geometric constraint

That is the right unifier.

So the best claim is:

In many domains where performance depends on how an interior couples to a boundary, the isoperimetric quotient E^2 is a plausible first-order screening feature.

That is respectable.

Where it likely helps

