	•	a compact shape score can help compare geometries quickly

Again: useful as a cheap pre-simulation metric, not a replacement for simulation.

Where the claim is too strong right now

These need much more caution:

Stress concentration

Stress concentration depends heavily on:
	•	local curvature
	•	notch radius
	•	load direction
	•	boundary conditions
	•	material behavior

A global scalar like E^2 will miss too much. It may correlate weakly with isotropy, but it will not directly predict stress concentration factors in general.

Antenna efficiency

RF behavior depends on much more than area/perimeter:
	•	resonance
	•	feed geometry
	•	current distribution
	•	wavelength scale
	•	substrate
	•	impedance matching

E^2 might be a morphology feature, but not a universal coupling ceiling.

Pipe flow

Hydraulic performance depends on more than area and perimeter alone, especially once you leave idealized laminar cases. A single scalar may help characterize compactness, but “universal hydraulic efficiency factor” is too strong.

Information theory

This is the most speculative unless you define a precise information functional. Right now it is analogy, not theorem.

